  <section class="section-pad" style="background:var(--bg);">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Signs Your Liverpool Boiler Needs Servicing Now</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">Do not wait for the annual reminder if your boiler is showing any of these signs. Call us and we can often attend the same day across Liverpool.</p>

      <div class="signs-grid">
        <div class="sign-item">
          <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Higher than usual gas bills</strong>
            <p>An inefficient boiler works harder to produce the same heat, using more gas in the process. A service can restore efficiency and reduce bills immediately.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-item">
          <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Boiler taking longer to heat the home</strong>
            <p>If your radiators are taking noticeably longer to warm up, scale build-up on the heat exchanger or a failing pump are common causes, both identifiable during a service.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-item">
          <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Unusual noises: banging, kettling or whistling</strong>
            <p>These sounds typically indicate limescale build-up, air in the system or a worn component. Left untreated they can lead to a complete breakdown.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-item" style="border-left-color:var(--red);">
          <span class="sign-icon" style="color:var(--red);">!</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Yellow or orange flame</strong>
            <p>The boiler flame should always be blue. A yellow or orange flame indicates incomplete combustion and a potential carbon monoxide risk. Call us immediately. See <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/carbon-monoxide-poisoning/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NHS carbon monoxide guidance</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-item">
          <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Boiler losing pressure repeatedly</strong>
            <p>A boiler that keeps losing pressure has either a small leak somewhere in the system or a failing pressure relief valve. Both are easily identified and usually resolved during a service visit.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-item">
          <span class="sign-icon">!</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Boiler has not been serviced in over 12 months</strong>
            <p>If you cannot remember when your boiler was last serviced it has almost certainly been too long. Book a service now to protect your warranty and avoid a winter breakdown.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

